{"key":"processedPost-9969603","value":{"id":9969603,"first":9968902,"last":9989162,"when":1237049417,"utime":"03/14/09 07:50 PM","content":"Cubensis doesn't require or even want a casing layer.&nbsp; However, you need to provide proper fruiting conditions of massive fresh air, bright fluorescent or natural light from a bright window, and 95% or so humidity.&nbsp; However you go about it is going to work.&nbsp; MGMC is the worst possible choice for a casing layer, as I've been saying here for years.&nbsp; It has lots of sticks and other wood in it, and potting soils are <i>designed</i> to grow trichoderma.&nbsp; Remember, trich is a beneficial organism in soil, and plants can't grow without it if they're being fed with manure or other organic fertilizers.&nbsp; Next time, fruit your coir uncased.&nbsp; If you need a humidity boost, lay a sheet of wax paper over the tray during primordia formation.<br />RR","title":"Re: MGMC vs 50/50+ (Wishing I hadn't jumped on the bandwagon)","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}